-- ── DataStax ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DataStax is a data platform company built on Apache Cassandra, best known for Astra DB, a cloud-native NoSQL and vector database used to power real-time and AI applications, and for Langflow, an open-source tool for building AI applications with large language models. Founded in 2010 as Riptano by Jonathan Ellis and Matt Pfeil, the company was later renamed DataStax and headquartered in Santa Clara, California. IBM announced its acquisition of DataStax in February 2025 and completed the deal in May 2025, folding DataStax's technology into IBM's watsonx AI and data portfolio.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Usage-based cloud pricing for Astra DB plus enterprise licensing, now offered through IBM$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Astra DB Free tier available with about 25 USD of monthly usage credit; Pay As You Go and Enterprise pricing scale from there$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Roughly 700 to 800 employees at the time of the IBM acquisition; now part of IBM$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Santa Clara, California, United States (now operating as part of IBM)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DataStax Review 2026: Astra DB Pricing After IBM Deal$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DataStax builds Astra DB and Langflow on Apache Cassandra. See 2026 pricing, features, and what the 2025 IBM acquisition means for customers.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DataStax is a data infrastructure company built around Apache Cassandra, the open-source, highly scalable NoSQL database originally developed at Facebook and later donated to the Apache Software Foundation. The company was founded in 2010 in Austin, Texas, as Riptano, by Jonathan Ellis and Matt Pfeil, two engineers who had worked with Cassandra at Rackspace; it was soon renamed DataStax and its headquarters moved to Santa Clara, California, where the company remained based through the mid-2020s. Over more than a decade, DataStax built a commercial business around Cassandra, offering DataStax Enterprise, a supported, hardened distribution of Cassandra for large organizations, and later Astra DB, a fully managed, cloud-native database-as-a-service built on Cassandra that DataStax launched in May 2020. Astra DB removed much of the operational burden of running Cassandra clusters directly, letting developers provision a serverless database, pay based on usage, and scale storage and throughput without managing nodes themselves. As interest in generative AI and retrieval-augmented generation applications grew, DataStax positioned Astra DB as a vector database, adding native vector search and storage so the same database could hold structured application data alongside embeddings used to power AI features such as semantic search and chatbot memory. Alongside Astra DB, DataStax also develops and maintains Langflow, an open-source, low-code visual tool for building applications powered by large language models, which lets developers assemble AI application logic, including prompts, retrieval steps, agents, and tool calls, as a connected flow rather than hand-written orchestration code. DataStax also contributes to and supports several other open-source projects in this space, including Apache Pulsar and OpenSearch. On February 25, 2025, IBM announced it had agreed to acquire DataStax, aiming to strengthen its watsonx portfolio of AI and data products with DataStax's NoSQL, vector database, and generative AI tooling, and to give enterprise customers a stronger foundation for building and deploying AI applications on top of large volumes of unstructured and real-time data. The deal closed on May 28, 2025, and DataStax's technology, including Astra DB and Langflow, is now offered as part of IBM's product portfolio. IBM has stated it will continue to support and engage with the open-source communities DataStax was involved in, including Apache Cassandra, Langflow, Apache Pulsar, and OpenSearch, rather than closing those projects off. At the time of the acquisition, DataStax had roughly 700 to 800 employees, though as part of IBM its resources, sales channels, and enterprise reach have expanded considerably. Astra DB's pricing follows a usage-based, tiered structure. A Free tier gives developers a way to explore the product at no cost, providing a recurring monthly usage credit of around 25 USD that covers a meaningful amount of storage and read and write operations, commonly cited as up to about 80GB of storage and 20 million read and write operations per month, making it practical for prototypes, side projects, and small production workloads. Beyond the free tier, a Pay As You Go plan charges per operation and per gigabyte of storage or data transfer with no upfront commitment, and pricing varies somewhat by cloud provider, including AWS, Google Cloud, or Azure, and region. An Enterprise, or Standard, tier adds features aimed at larger organizations such as private network endpoints, customer-managed encryption keys, multi-region deployment, and centralized organization management, typically negotiated directly with sales rather than published as a flat rate. Existing DataStax Enterprise customers running self-managed Cassandra deployments can continue to license that product separately from the cloud-hosted Astra DB service.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e4f5320d-cddc-4978-9d9b-313e103e6317';

